it. And this is something that we have learned over the years as well. We're a

00:13:35.119 --> 00:13:39.000
startup company, we basically started with an app and then that grew and that

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:43.679
built and more customers came on it. So we learned over the years that it's very

00:13:43.679 --> 00:13:47.599
important to if you have this massive app that can do a lot of stuff and that

00:13:47.599 --> 00:13:52.960
grows over time that your code is maintainable and that you can work with

00:13:52.960 --> 00:13:58.559
it. So how do you exactly make maintainable code because that's kind of

00:13:58.559 --> 00:14:05.359
a magic thing. These are principles that are, well, not necessarily for Shiny but

00:14:05.359 --> 00:14:10.640
for any app that you're developing in any software. It's important that you

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:15.520
write code which is easy to understand and debug, meaning that you think about

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:21.599
coding style, commenting your code, keep it stupid simple, the KISS principle. So

00:14:21.599 --> 00:14:25.320
that is always easy to understand. You can choose to write really complex code

00:14:25.359 --> 00:14:30.280
but that honestly never helped us because if you developed something very

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:33.320
complex with a very complex piece of code and then look at it a couple of

00:14:33.320 --> 00:14:38.440
months later, you're like, I don't know what was actually happening here, some

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:44.039
magic. And it does give me the desired outcome, but you have no clue what is

00:14:44.039 --> 00:14:49.440
actually going on there anymore. So keep it simple. We're also talking about

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:53.880
maintainable code, we're looking for an easy to modify and enhance code, meaning

00:14:53.880 --> 00:14:59.400
that don't repeat yourself or dry principle, meaning that if you need to

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:03.919
make a change to your code, because let's say in our app, we're going to add

00:15:03.960 --> 00:15:09.440
another data set, then obviously we don't want to do everything again. We

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:13.080
don't want to repeat our code. If we need to make changes need to happen fast

00:15:13.080 --> 00:15:20.080
because we want to have new features out fast. So build your code like that you

00:15:20.119 --> 00:15:25.440
can easily modify it. I'm going to talk a bit more about that later on and what

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:30.679
you can actually use and what we use to kind of don't repeat ourselves. Also

00:15:30.679 --> 00:15:35.760
separation is key. And I remember when I started working as a data scientist at

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:39.479
Dr. Reddy's and had to build my first shiny app. And I was super proud of the

00:15:39.479 --> 00:15:43.919
app because it had like, I don't know, 3000 lines of code in one script, which

00:15:43.919 --> 00:15:47.919
was F dot R. And I was like, Whoa, this is a really cool app, so many lines of

00:15:47.919 --> 00:15:55.599
code. Obviously, I didn't know what I knew now, obviously. Because separation,

00:15:55.640 --> 00:16:00.719
splitting your code up into small, easily consumable parts is essential.

00:16:00.919 --> 00:16:06.239
That app that I built in the early days, 3000 lines of code, not maintainable at

00:16:06.239 --> 00:16:11.280
all. If I needed to find something, it could take me minutes or maybe half an

00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:17.200
hour to actually search through code and make it all work. So what we do now at

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:22.080
Analytic Help is we separate basically every separate piece of functionality

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:28.119
into separate scripts. So that if also in separate directories, meaning that if we

00:16:28.119 --> 00:16:32.280
need to find something or a specific piece that does this or that, that we can

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:39.520
easily find it. Also, we need to have code that's easy to test. And there comes

00:16:39.799 --> 00:16:46.159
the automated units tests in place. If you have separated your code in like these

00:16:46.159 --> 00:16:52.080
churns, it's also easier to test only that script for the desired outcome. And

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:56.080
I'll also talk a little bit more about that later when I'm talking about how to

00:16:56.080 --> 00:17:04.439
functionize your code. Alright, so maintainable code, that's one thing. Then

00:17:04.439 --> 00:17:10.319
how are you going to organize your Shiny app? And how are we doing that? We have

00:17:10.479 --> 00:17:15.640
one way you can do it is Golem and the Almighty modules. Everybody talks about

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:20.880
modules, especially when you are talking about building enterprise apps, or

00:17:21.239 --> 00:17:25.079
building apps for production, or as soon as you come into the territory of more

00:17:25.280 --> 00:17:31.800
advanced Shiny apps, then there's no way to go around modules. And Golem is a

00:17:31.800 --> 00:17:35.680
package that based Golem is a package that actually helps you to build your

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:40.959
Shiny application as a package. So Golem is basically a framework for building

00:17:40.959 --> 00:17:44.680
your production grade Shiny application, it helps you to structure your code and

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:49.400
to organize it. And to basically be able to make your Shiny app as an R

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:53.880
package. If you have any experience with building R packages, it seems very

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:58.439
familiar to you. Because all the other things that you're used to of making

00:17:58.439 --> 00:18:02.920
functions in your package are also here as well. So it's super easy to document

00:18:02.959 --> 00:18:07.160
super easy to test. So coming back to how to build maintainable code, make sure

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:11.239
that you can test it. Golem kind of facilitates that. And obviously, because

00:18:11.319 --> 00:18:15.520
if you can package it, you can also easily share it. So that's also a great

00:18:15.520 --> 00:18:22.640
advantage. And it makes use of Shiny modules. So you hear a lot about modules.

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:27.560
But there's also another way that you can kind of manage or make maintainable

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:33.199
code. And that is functionalizing. I don't know if this is an actual word. But

00:18:33.199 --> 00:18:36.359
what I mean with functionalizing your R code is basically that you build your

00:18:36.359 --> 00:18:42.119
code up as functions. And this helps you to don't repeat yourself. Because if

00:18:42.119 --> 00:18:49.479
you're making functions out of several server scripts, or UI parts, then you can

00:18:49.479 --> 00:18:54.719
easily use those functions in other parts of the application. So coming back

00:18:54.719 --> 00:19:01.160
to my app, farming cloud data, or our app, I should say, sorry, farming cloud

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:06.839
data. And we what we do there is we provide access to different data sets. So

