using modules, for a variety of reasons, we chose to functionize the code, meaning

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:32.719
that if we now need to make an adjustment to, let's say, the download

00:19:32.719 --> 00:19:38.319
button, we can very easily do so by just changing that function. And functions are

00:19:39.599 --> 00:19:44.199
a fundamental unit of attraction in R, we use functions all the time, or build

00:19:44.199 --> 00:19:51.160
around functions. So it's very helpful to do that, at least like that, to help you

00:19:51.160 --> 00:19:57.359
to make your apps scalable. So what functions don't do is address the

00:19:57.359 --> 00:20:01.160
namespaces problem, because that is what modules do. So when you're using

00:20:01.160 --> 00:20:05.520
functions, you still need to make sure yourself that none of the input and

00:20:05.560 --> 00:20:11.160
output names or IDs have a conflict with each other. Because in a shiny app, you

00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:15.280
can't use the same IDs for inputs, or the same IDs for outputs, because then it

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:22.959
will just not work. So that is one downside of using functions. And yeah, as

00:20:22.959 --> 00:20:27.479
I said, you can use modules, because they add this one extra level of

00:20:27.479 --> 00:20:31.959
abstraction, and taking care of the namespaces problem. But functions will

00:20:31.959 --> 00:20:39.000
already get you, well, good, as a good start. Then another thing, another

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:43.680
framework that I want to highlight today, and if you know me already, then you

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:49.560
might have seen this. But it's about a new package Rhino. Rhino is developed by

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:55.280
Epsilon. And it's also a framework that kind of promises to help you build

00:20:55.280 --> 00:21:01.319
enterprise level shiny applications. So it kind of is similar to Golan, but

00:21:01.319 --> 00:21:04.959
something different. What Rhino does, I think it was only released a couple of

00:21:04.959 --> 00:21:10.239
weeks ago, what Rhino does is it helps you to have this kind of framework around

00:21:10.239 --> 00:21:14.439
building your shiny app, and helping you with all kinds of best practices, and

00:21:14.439 --> 00:21:17.839
giving you development tools. So it provides you with the basic structure of

00:21:17.839 --> 00:21:23.439
a project, it provides you with a folder structure, files, kind of the same as

00:21:23.439 --> 00:21:28.479
when you're using Golan. And it also provides tools to work with JavaScript

00:21:28.520 --> 00:21:35.479
and SAS, for example. So this one uses box to modularize code, meaning what box

00:21:35.479 --> 00:21:43.760
does, box basically makes our files, importable, as kind of modules, meaning

00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:49.199
that you can just write an R script, and then can import it using box. And then

00:21:49.199 --> 00:21:52.599
it works kind of the same as a module. So it's a bit different than the shiny

00:21:52.599 --> 00:21:58.839
modules work. And it's definitely an interesting concept. So it's actually

00:21:58.880 --> 00:22:05.800
also a little bit similar to chopping up like your big app.r script into multiple

00:22:06.119 --> 00:22:10.439
R scripts, and then importing them in another way, box kind of take care of

00:22:10.439 --> 00:22:15.560
that in a more clever way, so that you don't repeat yourself. Definitely worth

00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:23.359
a look. And the other thing now is, okay, you've built your code, you have nice,

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:30.560
nice code, nice structure, it's maintainable, you have built your, your

00:22:30.560 --> 00:22:35.160
kind of structure of your app using either Golan functions, Rhino, whatever

00:22:35.160 --> 00:22:39.239
there is, then it's always a question, how are you going to bring that to your

00:22:39.239 --> 00:22:43.280
users, you're going to use it. So a little bit about infrastructure and how

00:22:43.280 --> 00:22:50.000
we do that. Obviously, there are 1000s of ways you can do it. And I'm not saying

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:55.520
that the way we did it is like the most ultimate way to do it. But for us, it

00:22:55.520 --> 00:23:02.800
works very well. So these are my experiences, and our setup. And this is

00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:07.479
our infrastructure. So I've kind of simplified it here, then how it is in the

00:23:07.479 --> 00:23:12.199
real world, obviously. But our broad infrastructure, looking beyond shiny,

00:23:12.479 --> 00:23:17.319
looks like this. Like, first, we get our data somewhere. And we get data from the

00:23:17.319 --> 00:23:22.160
NHS, the National Health Service in the UK, then we do some stuff in R to

00:23:22.160 --> 00:23:26.920
transform it, clean it, validate it, etc. Then we send it somewhere to be stored.

00:23:27.199 --> 00:23:32.319
And we use bins and databases for that. If you're not familiar with bins, we

00:23:32.319 --> 00:23:39.319
definitely read up about it. It's just a nice way to store any R objects. Once we

00:23:39.319 --> 00:23:43.359
have our data somewhere, then we build tools around the data. As I said, we have

00:23:43.359 --> 00:23:48.239
API's using Plumber, we have shiny applications, but we also do our markdown

00:23:48.239 --> 00:23:54.359
reports and evil reports using the Stula. And then we deploy it. And we use RStudio

00:23:54.359 --> 00:23:59.239
Connect for that. So our API's and our shiny apps are deployed on RStudio

00:23:59.239 --> 00:24:03.599
Connect and are accessed from our customers outside of the organisation. You

00:24:03.599 --> 00:24:07.680
don't hear that a lot with RStudio Connect, people actually do that. But you

00:24:07.680 --> 00:24:11.880
can really nicely do that because you can also add your own branding to Connect,

00:24:12.119 --> 00:24:17.000
meaning that it's also perfectly usable for outside customers if they want to

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:21.520
access your application in a safe way. Because as I said, it's important for us

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:25.599
that there is some access control, so kind of a login mechanism. And RStudio

00:24:25.599 --> 00:24:31.359
Connect really takes care of that very well. So then we basically have our ETL,

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:35.680
our extract transform load, we have our apps, we have it deployed. And then

00:24:35.680 --> 00:24:40.119
obviously around that is monitoring, we need to make sure that every step of the

00:24:40.119 --> 00:24:46.599
process is being taken care of. Version control, meaning that we need to have,

00:24:46.640 --> 00:24:52.439
for example, our API, customers are directly able to access data via the API

00:24:52.439 --> 00:24:57.040
and can use the API in their own pipelines, dashboards, databases, etc. So

00:24:57.040 --> 00:24:59.920
it's very important to have a version control on there. Because if you release

00:24:59.920 --> 00:25:04.239
a new version and have breaking changes, what if the pipeline of the customer

00:25:04.239 --> 00:25:09.119
depends on that. So there's this whole versioning control system around our

00:25:09.119 --> 00:25:14.439
infrastructure. And then we also have a logging part, which I'm not going to go

00:25:14.439 --> 00:25:18.319
into detail about, but we just make sure that we know what's happening in every

00:25:18.319 --> 00:25:26.400
step of this process. And then if we zoom in a bit more to our infrastructure,

00:25:26.400 --> 00:25:32.000
when it comes to our applications on Connect, we have a shiny app, which I

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:37.160
showed you farming cloud data. And actually, the server part of the shiny

00:25:37.160 --> 00:25:42.239
app is not that interesting. Because what the shiny app does is it's making

00:25:42.239 --> 00:25:47.680
requests to the plumber API. So basically, our back end is being written

00:25:47.680 --> 00:25:53.880
as an API in plumber. This is not any different from, for example, writing few

00:25:53.880 --> 00:25:58.839
applications or applications in JavaScript, because there you often have

00:25:58.839 --> 00:26:02.599
front end and back end completely separated. Shiny brings them together.

00:26:03.040 --> 00:26:10.040
But in this case, we kind of chose to also separate it here. So we have an API

00:26:10.319 --> 00:26:15.079
that fetches the data from a database, in our case, databases in Azure. And the

00:26:15.079 --> 00:26:19.719
plumber API, then does some processing to retrieve the correct data, whatever was

00:26:19.719 --> 00:26:26.560
requested and sends it back to the application. The application server part

00:26:26.560 --> 00:26:31.040
is then only about okay, make a request. And we're done with it. The other thing

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:36.800
that the shiny application does is making use of pins. So as I briefly

00:26:36.800 --> 00:26:42.040
mentioned, pins are a way where you can store your objects. It's basically you

00:26:42.040 --> 00:26:45.479
could kind of compare it to a database, it's not the same, but it's a place where

00:26:45.479 --> 00:26:53.839
you store our related stuff. For example, data tables, models, objects, whatever

00:26:53.839 --> 00:26:59.319
you want, really, you can pin it. And then you can use these pins to kind of source

00:26:59.319 --> 00:27:04.160
your data into your application. So the shiny app, the only thing that's in the

00:27:04.160 --> 00:27:10.319
server part is actually making requests to another app, or another API, making

00:27:10.319 --> 00:27:13.839
requests to fetch some data, for example, what needs to be displayed in the

00:27:13.839 --> 00:27:18.000
pickers. So what are the choices, which active ingredients can people select,

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:23.400
which brands can people select, etc. And the most of the shiny, the code is

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:27.599
actually the front end. And that's all being functionalized. So basically, we

00:27:27.599 --> 00:27:30.920
have like a couple of functions for our whole user interface that provides kind

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:39.280
of 10 steps for 10 data sets and a dashboard and a favorite step, etc. So it

00:27:39.280 --> 00:27:44.520
is deployed on RStudio Connect, we only have one server available that kind of

00:27:44.520 --> 00:27:50.599
serves RStudio Connect, it's a good server and fits our needs. Obviously, if

00:27:50.599 --> 00:27:55.119
you have a very large audience of let's say 1000s of users, you might want to

00:27:55.119 --> 00:28:02.640
look into putting multiple servers, and then kind of load balancing across these

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:07.040
servers, which RStudio Connect is also capable of, but we just have one. And

00:28:07.040 --> 00:28:14.400
what we kind of do to make sure that our apps are accessible, and fast is we have

00:28:14.439 --> 00:28:20.280
always a couple of R processes running at minimum to serve these apps. For

00:28:20.280 --> 00:28:23.839
example, for the plumber API, we have five processes always running and for

00:28:23.839 --> 00:28:28.239
the shiny app also five, meaning that there are 10 processes, R processes,

00:28:28.479 --> 00:28:33.119
always running to server applications so that people quickly can access the

00:28:33.119 --> 00:28:37.640
application and do whatever they want there. And I will come back to that a

00:28:37.640 --> 00:28:41.760
little bit about this process configuration and how these minimum

00:28:41.760 --> 00:28:48.359
number of processes work. But this is kind of our base infrastructure, if I

00:28:48.400 --> 00:28:55.400
really simplify it. And I can also give you that as the biggest tip, we've seen

00:28:55.400 --> 00:29:00.839
a lot of benefits with using an API plumber API, instead of doing everything

00:29:00.839 --> 00:29:06.000
in that one session in the shiny application itself. So kind of we

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:10.439
separated it, that makes it one more maintainable and two faster as well,

00:29:10.640 --> 00:29:14.359
because we can kind of spread or load between what the app is doing on the

00:29:14.359 --> 00:29:18.560
front end versus what is happening in the back end. And we can also do those

00:29:18.560 --> 00:29:25.760
things in parallel. As I said, this is just one way how we do it. There are

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:30.560
obviously a bunch of alternatives. I'm not going into too much detail about it.

00:29:30.560 --> 00:29:34.479
But just so you know, there are multiple solutions to to achieve

00:29:36.040 --> 00:29:41.280
deployment of your application for for an enterprise. And one thing that you

00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:45.199
can do, if your app grows bigger and has more traffic, you can add load

00:29:45.199 --> 00:29:49.160
balancing and high availability using RStudio Connect, meaning that you kind

00:29:49.160 --> 00:29:56.199
of configure RStudio Connect to be across multiple servers. And then

00:29:56.280 --> 00:30:02.640
setting up an external shared file server that kind of then serves as the

00:30:05.119 --> 00:30:10.400
where all the files are stored for RStudio Connect. And then you have a

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:15.839
lot of solutions with Docker, obviously, what kind of RStudio Connect does

00:30:15.880 --> 00:30:20.599
under the hood, Docker is something that you can do separately to kind of ship

00:30:20.599 --> 00:30:25.760
your application with this environment to a server, whatever server that may

00:30:25.760 --> 00:30:30.359
be. And then your app is being run there. And Azure can be used for that

00:30:30.359 --> 00:30:33.920
Azure App Service, but also any other cloud service provider really has these

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:37.959
these options to do that. And then there's also Shiny Server open source,

00:30:38.119 --> 00:30:44.199
which is a fully open source solution where you can also which you can add to

00:30:44.199 --> 00:30:48.040
one of your service if you want and serve your application from there. So

00:30:48.160 --> 00:30:53.760
there are lots of alternatives. And I can talk for hours about how you can set

00:30:53.760 --> 00:30:58.239
that up and how you can do that and going into the technicalities. But it is

00:30:58.239 --> 00:31:05.359
just to give you a brief overview of what options there are, and that RStudio

00:31:05.359 --> 00:31:13.880
Connect is one of them. So we've optimized, we did not optimize Shiny yet,

00:31:13.920 --> 00:31:18.520
but we have deployed our application somewhere. So we've written a code, and

00:31:18.560 --> 00:31:23.359
we've made it maintainable, we have built a structure, and we have thought

00:31:23.359 --> 00:31:28.760
about user experience. So we've deployed it somewhere. So now it's time to go

00:31:28.760 --> 00:31:33.640
look into a bit more detail into how we can optimize Shiny, to kind of make sure

00:31:33.680 --> 00:31:37.719
that everybody who wants to access the application at a given point in time can

00:31:37.719 --> 00:31:43.319
also do so. And the first thing I'm going to talk about with you is process

00:31:43.319 --> 00:31:48.119
configuration. And I quickly touched upon this when I said that we always have

00:31:48.439 --> 00:31:54.079
five R processes running for our Shiny app and for our Plumber API. Because, as

00:31:54.079 --> 00:31:59.319
you might know, a Shiny app or a Plumber API requires an R process, meaning that

00:31:59.359 --> 00:32:04.239
R needs to be up and running, and that needs to be ready to do stuff. And you

00:32:04.239 --> 00:32:08.239
can configure these kind of settings. And these kind of settings that I

00:32:08.239 --> 00:32:12.839
mentioned here, maximum processes, minimum processes, maximum connections

00:32:12.839 --> 00:32:19.400
per process, load factor, you can set them in most cases yourself. So in

00:32:19.400 --> 00:32:23.959
shinyapps.io, which is not an enterprise solution, but if you're still there,

00:32:24.359 --> 00:32:29.599
these settings will also be there in RStudio Connect. And it's just very

00:32:29.599 --> 00:32:35.439
important, also for if you are deploying your app in for any other cloud service

00:32:35.439 --> 00:32:40.000
provider, it's important to understand how this works and how you are kind of

00:32:40.119 --> 00:32:46.319
redirecting your users to an R process. Because a Shiny app requires an R

00:32:46.319 --> 00:32:50.239
process. Okay, so then there is an R process in the Shiny app. And then

00:32:50.239 --> 00:32:56.560
there's also a user. So a user can basically hop on to that R process. And

00:32:56.560 --> 00:33:01.239
you can say, okay, I want to have only one user for our process, or I want to

00:33:01.239 --> 00:33:05.000
have multiple and that is kind of going to determine your scalability of the

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:11.040
application. So things that you can tweak, for example, are the maximum

00:33:11.079 --> 00:33:16.839
number of processes that you are allowing to run for your Shiny app. If

00:33:16.839 --> 00:33:20.199
you said it's very high, let's say the maximum number of process can be 40, I

00:33:20.199 --> 00:33:25.560
don't know, 50,000, whatever you choose. And it also means that it's more

00:33:25.599 --> 00:33:31.160
resource consuming. Because the more R processes you have running on your

00:33:31.160 --> 00:33:35.239
server, the more that server is going to be occupied with actually maintaining

00:33:35.239 --> 00:33:40.439
and managing all those R processes. So you need to be a bit considerate here

00:33:40.439 --> 00:33:47.599
about okay, how many processes do I really need? And am I potentially

00:33:47.599 --> 00:33:54.680
overloading my server, the minimum number of processes is means you have, as

00:33:54.680 --> 00:33:58.599
in our case, a minimum number of processes running for your Shiny app at

00:33:58.599 --> 00:34:07.119
any point in time. So if you set this higher, let's say 10, 15, 15, it means

00:34:07.119 --> 00:34:11.520
that you also consume more resources. Because all these processes are running,

00:34:11.520 --> 00:34:16.399
they consume memory of your server. So the higher you set this, the more

00:34:16.399 --> 00:34:19.679
resource consuming it will be. So you need to think about that. In our case,

00:34:19.679 --> 00:34:24.320
we chose for five minimum processes. Because if we're looking at the number

00:34:24.320 --> 00:34:27.560
of users that are coming at the simultaneous time to the app, and are

00:34:27.560 --> 00:34:31.840
doing stuff, this is more than enough. But if you have the minimum number of

00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:36.120
processes set, it means that there's always an R process running for your

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:40.199
application, meaning that the startup in time will increase drastically.

00:34:40.479 --> 00:34:45.840
Because and that's kind of the downside of building a Shiny app, the R process

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:52.120
needs to be startup. So besides loading your app, it also needs to load an R

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:56.840
session. So together, that can take a lot of time and people don't like to

00:34:56.840 --> 00:35:02.760
wait. And especially if you are building apps for a larger audience, apps that

00:35:02.760 --> 00:35:07.600
people pay for, you have to have high expectations, people can't wait 40

00:35:07.600 --> 00:35:12.479
seconds for the app to load, needs to be 10 seconds max. And if there's any

00:35:12.479 --> 00:35:17.000
loading time at all, then it needs to be some kind of user friendly way of

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:22.399
loading with kind of spinners and waiters and whatever. But this is really

00:35:22.399 --> 00:35:26.479
important for us to make sure that our app is fast. Also, when it's starting

00:35:26.520 --> 00:35:32.280
up. Then you have the maximum connections per process, which means how

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:39.399
many users are you letting on to each R process. If you set this very low, it

00:35:39.399 --> 00:35:44.560
means that, for example, in our case, we have set it to one. There's only one

00:35:44.560 --> 00:35:48.919
user allowed per process, because otherwise, users have to wait for each

00:35:48.919 --> 00:35:53.399
other. Because if one user is pushing a button to do a calculation, and the

00:35:53.399 --> 00:35:57.360
other, then the session is basically occupied. And we all know when an R

00:35:57.360 --> 00:36:02.959
session is occupied, then you can, you kind of can give an assignment or a

00:36:02.959 --> 00:36:07.600
calculation, but R won't do anything until the previous one is executed. So

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.199
we've chosen to set our maximum connection per session per process to

00:36:12.199 --> 00:36:18.199
one. But it really depends on how your app is working and what is best for you.

00:36:18.679 --> 00:36:23.560
But the lower you set it, the less load there will be per process, but it will

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:28.919
also be more resource consuming. So we constantly see here already the kind of

00:36:28.919 --> 00:36:33.360
the decision you need to make between how many resources do I want to invest

00:36:33.840 --> 00:36:41.239
versus how dedicated do I want my processes to be. The last one is load

00:36:41.239 --> 00:36:46.959
factor. That's a value between zero and one and the lower means that you spin up

00:36:46.959 --> 00:36:51.639
many new processes. So you can also if you have the maximum number of

00:36:51.639 --> 00:36:54.719
connections per process set to five, for example, five users can

00:36:54.719 --> 00:36:59.760
simultaneously access your R session. If you set it very low, it means that as

00:36:59.760 --> 00:37:03.520
soon as these people start hitting buttons and doing calculations and asking

00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:08.159
things from the R session, that they get redirected to another process or that

00:37:08.159 --> 00:37:12.719
the new process is being spun up to kind of handle that load. In our case, it

00:37:12.719 --> 00:37:18.000
doesn't matter because we only have one connection per session. But it could

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:23.520
mean a lot. Like playing around with these settings can drastically change

00:37:23.520 --> 00:37:29.719
the performance of your app. I remember from previous apps that I deployed using

00:37:29.719 --> 00:37:35.040
either I think it was even called RStudio Shiny Server or something like

00:37:35.040 --> 00:37:43.600
that back in the days. But you can see changes pretty soon when you are playing

00:37:43.600 --> 00:37:48.320
around with these settings. So keep that in mind. So that's one thing that you can

00:37:48.320 --> 00:37:54.159
optimize. But most of the game really is to be made in the app itself. So how are

00:37:54.159 --> 00:37:59.120
you going to make your app fast? How are you going to make your app enjoyable?

00:38:00.080 --> 00:38:05.360
Because that is part of building enterprise-grade apps. They need to work great.

00:38:05.360 --> 00:38:13.280
People expect a lot from them. So smart coding. How are we going to speed up our

00:38:13.280 --> 00:38:19.040
Shiny application? One way we can do that is by using cache. And cache is an

00:38:19.040 --> 00:38:27.679
interesting way of kind of reducing the time it takes to get output. So imagine

00:38:27.679 --> 00:38:31.120
that people can hit a button in your Shiny app. And once they hit that button,

00:38:31.760 --> 00:38:36.879
there will be a very lengthy calculation running. I don't know. Maybe you have some

00:38:36.879 --> 00:38:42.959
kind of machine learning model or something. But they choose one input. And the

00:38:42.959 --> 00:38:47.919
calculation runs and it gets an output. It's obviously a shame if then a second user

00:38:47.919 --> 00:38:52.959
comes in, chooses the exact same input, does the calculation again, and gets the exact

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:57.520
same output again. It's kind of a waste of time. Why should you do that calculation

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:02.719
twice? So this is where cache comes in. Because what you also can do is say, okay,

00:39:02.719 --> 00:39:11.439
well, the first user requested a result for this input. Input A, we call it. We do that

00:39:11.439 --> 00:39:15.600
lengthy calculation. Yes, it takes some time. But for the next ones, the next users,

00:39:15.600 --> 00:39:20.719
we're not going to do that. No. Instead, we're going to immediately use the results that were

00:39:20.719 --> 00:39:26.399
being cached from that calculation. So cache is basically a way of storing your output

00:39:27.520 --> 00:39:33.280
somewhere, in this case, on your server or wherever you choose to store it. And then

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:38.159
retrieving it from storage instead of doing the calculation. So especially if you have a large

00:39:38.159 --> 00:39:44.159
audience for your app, it can save a lot of time. And especially if a large audience is doing many

00:39:44.159 --> 00:39:51.360
of the same things. And not only if you have a large audience, even if you have just one user

00:39:51.360 --> 00:39:59.120
using your app, but it's constantly switching between input A, B, C, A, B, C, B again, C again.

00:39:59.120 --> 00:40:04.639
It's kind of requesting constantly that same calculation because he's just shifting inputs

00:40:04.639 --> 00:40:10.239
and he forgets kind of what the outcome of A was, so goes back again. So even for single users,

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:17.120
it can be very beneficial to just store these results. There are two ways you can implement

00:40:17.120 --> 00:40:23.919
cache in Shiny. The first is the memoirs package, which kind of helps you to store functions

00:40:25.199 --> 00:40:29.199
and the result of those functions as cache. And you have Shiny's bind cache function.

00:40:31.199 --> 00:40:37.520
I have an example of both of them on my GitHub page, and I will share that afterwards.

00:40:38.479 --> 00:40:45.520
So cache sounds nice, but a couple of disclaimers. It's obviously only useful when your output does

00:40:45.520 --> 00:40:52.879
not change and does not change often. So let's say that your output changes, I don't know,

00:40:52.879 --> 00:40:57.360
because there's a random seed in there or whatever. It changes every time, yet there's no point.

00:40:57.360 --> 00:41:03.760
It also is not that much point if your data behind it changes like every, I don't know, six hours

00:41:04.639 --> 00:41:10.639
or every day. It only is useful when it doesn't change regularly, so that is actually a point

00:41:10.639 --> 00:41:16.560
of storing your output. Then the downside of using cache is that it requires space,

00:41:16.560 --> 00:41:21.199
because obviously output needs to be stored somewhere, and that requires some space.

00:41:21.840 --> 00:41:27.679
And you need to think about sensitive data as well, because if you are kind of sharing your

00:41:27.679 --> 00:41:34.639
cached results with your other users, you need to think about, okay, is user A allowed to see

00:41:35.600 --> 00:41:42.399
whatever user C did? Is that output for them the same? Is that something that they

00:41:42.399 --> 00:41:46.879
both should be able to access? So that's something that you need to think about.

00:41:46.879 --> 00:41:50.080
But cache can be a game changer in the performance of your app.

00:41:50.879 --> 00:41:58.479
Another smart thing you can do is using background processes, and I touched upon it a bit by saying

00:41:58.479 --> 00:42:03.520
that if you have multiple users per connection, that they have to wait for each other because

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:10.560
the session is occupied. Well, that sometimes can happen, and we don't want that, because we don't

00:42:10.560 --> 00:42:16.000
want to have parallel execution. No, we want to have asynchronous execution of code, especially

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:20.800
if you're developing an app for multiple users. You want them to be able to do things at the same

00:42:20.800 --> 00:42:30.959
time and not be affected. And in fact, you also don't want a user to have to wait while something

00:42:30.959 --> 00:42:37.040
is being calculated and that he or she cannot do anything in the app. So let's say a user hits a

00:42:37.040 --> 00:42:42.080
button to kind of render a graph, and then in the background, some data is being retrieved from the

00:42:42.479 --> 00:42:48.399
database, and then calculations are being done, and then the graph is being rendered. Well, maybe the

00:42:48.399 --> 00:42:53.280
user doesn't want to wait those, I don't know, 30 seconds for the graph to show up, but maybe in

00:42:53.280 --> 00:42:58.479
between, the user wants to look at another table and maybe hit another button for a lighter

00:42:58.479 --> 00:43:05.840
calculation or another calculation. You don't want people to wait. So this is where caller comes

00:43:06.639 --> 00:43:13.520
into play, because with caller, you can spin a background R process. And this is really cool,

00:43:13.520 --> 00:43:19.120
because your Shiny app is running on one R process, and then you can use the caller to kind of set up

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:26.159
an additional R process, do the calculations there, then fetch the result, and put it back into the

00:43:26.159 --> 00:43:32.879
current R process. So this is especially useful if you have queries to databases, which take a very

00:43:32.879 --> 00:43:40.800
long time. And this is actually the exact same thing that we do with our API, in fact, and our

00:43:40.800 --> 00:43:48.159
Shiny app, because we actually let another R process do the work, retrieve the data from the

00:43:48.159 --> 00:43:55.360
database, and then kind of send the results back. That's a similar principle to caller, only here

00:43:55.360 --> 00:44:02.719
you do it in the Shiny app at the same time. And this is also useful, for example, when you are

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:08.479
starting up your application. So on startup, most often a bunch of data has to be loaded,

00:44:08.479 --> 00:44:13.280
and you want to display graphs and tables and whatever. It might be useful if you just say,

00:44:13.280 --> 00:44:17.919
okay, I'll just give it a little boost, and on startup, I'll spin up multiple processes

00:44:17.919 --> 00:44:25.040
for my application. And it works really nice. Caller shuts itself down when the process is done,

00:44:25.040 --> 00:44:31.280
and it's just a really nice and clean way to kind of put some extra resources to your Shiny app.

00:44:33.520 --> 00:44:42.479
Then another thing about the API, how you can speed that up. Because as I said,

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:48.000
our app is about retrieving data from the API, displaying it, and making it available to

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:55.919
download. So in our case, it means the faster our API is, the faster our Shiny app is. Because

00:44:56.800 --> 00:45:03.520
even though we are pulling in, I don't know, 100,000 lines of data whenever somebody makes

00:45:03.520 --> 00:45:10.080
a request, we want that to happen in a split second. What we want to avoid is people have

00:45:10.080 --> 00:45:14.479
to wait even 10 seconds for their data, because one of the selling points of our app is it's super

00:45:14.479 --> 00:45:20.479
fast. So for us, it's very important that the API is fast, so the Shiny app can be fast.

00:45:21.360 --> 00:45:28.479
And one of the real game changers for our app and our API was, is that we were going to use

00:45:28.479 --> 00:45:36.320
Feather instead of JSON. Like a Plumber API, by default, returns JSON, but you can also let it

00:45:36.320 --> 00:45:43.040
default to other data formats, for example, Feather. And we found that Feather is almost

00:45:44.639 --> 00:45:50.239
two and a half times faster in comparison to JSON, and also the file size is being reduced.

00:45:50.239 --> 00:45:57.280
Because we have to send data from the API to the app, the more data we have to send in terms

00:45:57.280 --> 00:46:04.479
of size, the longer it's going to take. So by implementing Feather and sending it over as a

00:46:04.479 --> 00:46:11.280
smaller Feather file, it was very, it took, it saved a lot of time to actually send that Feather

00:46:11.280 --> 00:46:17.439
file instead of a JSON file. And in some cases, we were actually able to reduce API response time

00:46:17.439 --> 00:46:24.719
by as much as 50%. And those are massive numbers. We're very happy that we've used Feather,

00:46:24.719 --> 00:46:31.760
and you can use Feather in any situation. So let's say that you are reading in a file from disk,

00:46:31.760 --> 00:46:35.919
for example, try to convert it to a Feather file, and then read it in as a Feather file.

00:46:36.479 --> 00:46:43.199
And most often you are way faster, even with, even faster than like functions like app read

00:46:43.199 --> 00:46:52.800
for reading a CSV and whatever. This is a really cool way to speed up your Shiny application.

00:46:56.159 --> 00:47:02.879
All right. So I hope these kind of tips helped you to kind of have some ideas about how you can

00:47:02.879 --> 00:47:09.360
improve your Shiny application, and how you can make your app faster, and how we did it.

00:47:09.840 --> 00:47:14.479
So this was kind of the stuff that I wanted to talk about when it comes to coding.

00:47:15.840 --> 00:47:21.280
Now I want to talk a bit about testing, because it's obviously very important that if you have an

00:47:21.280 --> 00:47:29.760
app for like users, enterprise users, customers who are relying on a daily basis on the information

00:47:29.760 --> 00:47:36.080
that you have in the application, you obviously want to test it. You want to test to make sure

00:47:36.080 --> 00:47:42.159
that it can handle the load that you're giving it. And you want to be able to test

00:47:43.760 --> 00:47:50.080
if it's working as expected anyway. So does your app every morning, do you know if it's running?

00:47:50.080 --> 00:47:55.120
Or do you have to check yourself? How can you be sure that at any point in time your app

00:47:55.120 --> 00:48:01.520
does what it is supposed to do? So first, we're going to take a look at the first question asked.

00:48:02.479 --> 00:48:08.879
Is your app ready for the load that it's supposed to handle? So we need to test for load.

00:48:10.159 --> 00:48:14.560
And testing for load we can do with a package called Shiny Load Test. And Shiny Load Test

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:20.399
provides the command line tool called Shiny Cannon. And because I find Shiny Cannon a lot

00:48:20.399 --> 00:48:26.719
cooler than Shiny Load Test, I put that as the headline. And this basically can answer the

00:48:26.719 --> 00:48:32.399
question for you, how many users can your Shiny app support? And it's really cool because the

00:48:32.399 --> 00:48:38.560
only thing that you need to do is record your R session like you're a normal user. And then you

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:44.959
kind of let Shiny Load Test simulate all those recordings and replay them in parallel, meaning

00:48:44.959 --> 00:48:51.439
that it can kind of simulate the situation in which multiple users at the same time are going

00:48:51.439 --> 00:48:56.879
to access your app. And then after that, you can analyze the results. Shiny Load Test has a bunch

00:48:56.879 --> 00:49:02.639
of convenient functions in there that allow you to analyze all the files that it generates. And

00:49:02.639 --> 00:49:07.679
then you can build nice looking reports. And these reports can, for example, tell you the time it

00:49:07.679 --> 00:49:17.280
takes to load the HTML home page or the time it takes to grab your CSS or JavaScript files

00:49:17.280 --> 00:49:24.399
or the starting time of the session. So how long it actually takes before Shiny connects

00:49:24.399 --> 00:49:31.840
to Socket.js. Also calculation time of, for example, any button that you press or any graph

00:49:31.840 --> 00:49:38.560
that you try to render or table that you're going to display. And you also get a lot of details

00:49:38.560 --> 00:49:45.600
about individual events. And a bunch of information is here. And this makes sure that you know,

00:49:46.479 --> 00:49:51.760
OK, my app can safely handle this load. And then you need to see, OK, does it actually fit my

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:56.719
expectation of how many people are going to visit the app? Or do I need to change something?

00:49:57.679 --> 00:50:03.520
It's also great to find out what is taking the most time and where you can get some efficiency

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:11.280
gains. So we test for load. Another thing that we want to test is test for outcome.

00:50:12.159 --> 00:50:17.840
And testing for outcome means that we want to be sure that when somebody pushes a button,

00:50:18.879 --> 00:50:23.360
that the outcome is what we expected. And we can test for outcome with the package called

00:50:23.360 --> 00:50:29.360
ShinyTest2. It's actually the follow up of the package called ShinyTest. No surprises there.

00:50:30.560 --> 00:50:35.520
And this package you can use to create and run automated tests. And behind the hood,

00:50:35.520 --> 00:50:40.560
it uses TestStats. So what you kind of do here in this package is also you record,

00:50:40.560 --> 00:50:46.080
just like Shiny load test, you record the session. And then you kind of replay it.

00:50:47.280 --> 00:50:53.520
But in this case, ShinyTest2 will translate your actions into actual code. It's really cool. It's

00:50:53.520 --> 00:51:00.800
like magic. But it will write actual unit tests for you using TestStats. So this allows you then

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:06.080
to kind of everybody talks about our units that are a pain, and they take a lot of effort,

00:51:06.080 --> 00:51:09.520
there's so much time, and I don't have time to write them and always forget it.

00:51:09.520 --> 00:51:14.639
This makes it super easy. I mean, it doesn't get easier than that. You just

00:51:15.280 --> 00:51:18.399
play around in the app, you click a few things, and the code is there for you.

00:51:19.919 --> 00:51:26.879
This package uses Chrome modes to launch a Chrome browser, a headless one. And it's

00:51:27.120 --> 00:51:32.800
a really cool way to kind of make sure that your app is doing what it's supposed to do.

00:51:33.360 --> 00:51:40.479
Plus, what the thing that's up to you, and it's your responsibility, is you need to update those

00:51:40.479 --> 00:51:45.120
tests whenever you are making a deployment or whatsoever. If you don't update your tests,

00:51:45.919 --> 00:51:52.879
then it's pretty useless. But it's a nice way to be confident about releasing your application with

00:51:52.879 --> 00:51:57.120
a new update. Because unfortunately, when you change, and we all know that, when you change

00:51:57.120 --> 00:52:03.360
somewhere in one part of the app, another thing might break. And this kind of prevents that.

00:52:03.360 --> 00:52:10.159
So this is really key to make sure that you don't ship anything to production before it's really

00:52:10.159 --> 00:52:19.360
good. So I'm moving on to the last part I want to tell you something about how to monitor app

