more easy to use and also more clean. It cleans itself up pretty easily, while sometimes with

01:01:10.239 --> 01:01:17.439
Promises, some stuff lingers around and keeps lingering around. And we didn't find those

01:01:17.439 --> 01:01:21.840
issues with Caller. So that's why we use that instead. But it works the same as a Promise.

01:01:22.399 --> 01:01:28.399
Caller is nothing more or less, except for a couple of benefits or maybe disadvantages,

01:01:28.399 --> 01:01:34.879
compared to Promises. So, yeah, I hope that answers that. Great. Thank you. Sorry,

01:01:34.879 --> 01:01:41.919
I'm just firing this away at you right now. Someone else was interested in Rhino and said,

01:01:41.919 --> 01:01:48.399
for beginners with Shiny, would you recommend Golem or Rhino? Oh, that's a good question.

01:01:48.639 --> 01:01:57.199
I don't know, for beginners. I'm actually tempted to say Rhino. I don't know why, but I do have a

01:01:57.199 --> 01:02:04.800
feeling that, especially with the documentation they provided, it could be really a cool way to

01:02:04.800 --> 01:02:12.320
set up your project. And for me, when I was looking at Rhino, it felt more intuitively

01:02:13.120 --> 01:02:20.320
compared to Golem. If you have built R packages before, then I definitely think Golem would be

01:02:21.520 --> 01:02:26.800
a good first step, because it sounds very familiar then to you. But if you don't have experience with

01:02:26.800 --> 01:02:32.719
package building, maybe I would say pick Rhino and see what you can make of it. A little disclaimer,

01:02:32.719 --> 01:02:38.000
Rhino is still super new and in development. So also the developers say there might be some

01:02:38.959 --> 01:02:45.679
glitches here and there, obviously, teething issues. So that's just a little disclaimer.

01:02:45.679 --> 01:02:52.560
But yeah, I would maybe say Rhino. Awesome. Another question that's just

01:02:52.560 --> 01:02:58.879
being upvoted right now from David is, the myth is that only Python can be used

01:02:58.879 --> 01:03:04.000
for production-grade apps. What made you choose to use R? Was it Shiny?

01:03:08.239 --> 01:03:12.800
I chose R, like in university, back in the day as a scientist, I learned two programming languages,

01:03:12.800 --> 01:03:19.840
R and Python, obviously. I stuck with R because I was mainly active in the pharmaceutical industry

01:03:19.840 --> 01:03:26.479
and R is there just, it's more preferred above Python, probably because it's from where it's

01:03:26.479 --> 01:03:32.080
coming from. I think it's definitely a myth that only Python can be used for production-grade apps.

01:03:32.800 --> 01:03:39.840
Look, the language doesn't really matter. As I said, we built a Plumber API using R,

01:03:39.840 --> 01:03:44.879
which is just R. We built an outstanding API that is being used in production pipelines for

01:03:44.879 --> 01:03:50.879
other companies right now and nobody knows and nobody really cares. What people care about is,

01:03:50.879 --> 01:03:57.840
okay, an API needs to be quick, it needs to deliver what I want it to do, like maybe the data,

01:03:57.840 --> 01:04:03.280
and whether it's written in R, Python, JavaScript, Node, they don't really care. It just needs to be

01:04:04.159 --> 01:04:09.280
up to standards and you can achieve that with R as well. Obviously, it's nice that,

01:04:10.080 --> 01:04:16.879
because I knew R, that there was Shiny, so it was like the step was more easy to make,

01:04:16.879 --> 01:04:24.399
to build a Shiny application. I learned a few end nodes later on in my career after Shiny,

01:04:25.040 --> 01:04:32.320
but I must say, even though I have seen a few end nodes, we're still using Shiny for

01:04:34.159 --> 01:04:38.479
enterprise-grade apps, just because there is a fast development.

01:04:39.679 --> 01:04:45.040
It's fast to develop extra features for the app and the performance is just really good,

01:04:45.040 --> 01:04:50.159
as long as you know how to use it and how to design it. That's why I said at the beginning,

01:04:51.040 --> 01:04:54.479
some people said to me, oh, your app doesn't look like a Shiny app.

01:04:54.479 --> 01:05:02.000
Yeah, but we build an app. How we build it should be irrelevant and we did this with Shiny, so

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:09.600
yeah, definitely admit that I'm ready to bust. I love it. Someone else asked,

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:14.239
is Feather strictly better than using JSON or what are the drawbacks?

01:05:14.560 --> 01:05:22.239
It is strictly better. Well, I don't think you can always say it's 100% better in some use cases.

01:05:23.120 --> 01:05:28.320
I'm sure it will be better than the other. For one thing, Feather, not everybody knows

01:05:28.320 --> 01:05:35.360
how to deal with that. In our API as well, we've given our users the option, which output format

01:05:35.360 --> 01:05:38.800
do you want to have returned? Do you want to have JSON or do you want to have Feather? Because

01:05:39.600 --> 01:05:45.520
if our clients, it also depends on their end. Can they read in Feather files? Do they have

01:05:45.520 --> 01:05:55.679
tools with that? Are they comfortable working with it, et cetera? But it's not really different.

01:05:55.679 --> 01:06:08.479
It's just data that you are transferring and then you need to unpack it. We've seen,

01:06:08.560 --> 01:06:15.360
especially file size reduction and speed reading it in, and in our case, that was better.

01:06:17.199 --> 01:06:24.959
So yeah, that's all I can say about it. Thank you. I know we originally scheduled to

01:06:25.600 --> 01:06:29.840
15 minutes past the hour, so I want to see if you have time for a few more questions.

01:06:30.399 --> 01:06:39.040
Awesome. There is a great question I see that came in on Slido. Where do you see the line

01:06:39.040 --> 01:06:46.639
between BI and Shiny for your use cases? What positives and or limitations would you say

01:06:46.639 --> 01:06:54.399
about both? So just to clarify, what is meant with BI, like tools like Power BI and stuff?

01:06:55.360 --> 01:07:00.399
Yes. I'm assuming like business intelligence tools like Tableau and Power BI.

01:07:01.679 --> 01:07:11.840
Okay. Luke, if you want to build a simple standard dashboard with standard graphs and tables,

01:07:12.560 --> 01:07:16.800
why not use Power BI if you have access to the tool and your team kind of knows it?

01:07:17.360 --> 01:07:24.239
But as soon as you want to do custom things, you want to have a special graph. You want to

01:07:24.320 --> 01:07:30.479
have special functionality. I mean, we wanted to have a favorite test. So people could actually

01:07:30.479 --> 01:07:34.959
select their favorite products, and then that was being stored. It's being stored in the database,

01:07:34.959 --> 01:07:39.280
and then the pickers kind of, they can make a choice. Do you want to see only your favorites?

01:07:39.280 --> 01:07:44.239
Do you want to see everything? How are you going to do that in Power BI? Obviously,

01:07:45.280 --> 01:07:50.080
if you want, you can do everything probably. But then for this level of customization,

01:07:50.080 --> 01:07:56.800
I would say Shiny. So assume as you are looking at more customized features,

01:07:56.800 --> 01:08:01.760
building things your own way, especially if you know how to leverage Shiny with custom JavaScript

01:08:01.760 --> 01:08:06.479
and stuff, then the sky is the limit. And I would not choose for a standard,

01:08:07.600 --> 01:08:14.000
in my eyes, a standard Power BI dashboard. And it's like, because it's a web app,

01:08:14.879 --> 01:08:20.000
a Shiny is a web app, people can access it from wherever they are, whether they have access to

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:27.680
Power BI, yes or not. So it's, that's good. And like positives and limitations.

01:08:29.520 --> 01:08:38.000
Yeah, I think I covered that. Yeah. Awesome. One other question was any tips,

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:42.399
advice or resources for enterprise grade UI development?

01:08:42.399 --> 01:08:46.640
So interested to hear how you make an app look less like a Shiny app.

01:08:50.959 --> 01:08:57.520
Yeah, good question. Like we have UX designers who occasionally design stuff for us and then

01:08:57.520 --> 01:09:05.439
we just build it. What we did in some occasions was building HTML tools ourselves. So with the

01:09:05.439 --> 01:09:13.520
HTML widget package, we build an own widget that kind of was a multi-page form. So we kind of,

01:09:13.520 --> 01:09:19.359
we kind of built, if there's not a user interface component available in anything open source,

01:09:19.359 --> 01:09:25.759
we just build it ourselves. But one package that greatly helps to instantly make your app

01:09:25.759 --> 01:09:32.959
look better in a split second, bs4dash. bs4dash is awesome. It's a bootstrap based package.

01:09:34.640 --> 01:09:40.479
And bs4dash basically turns your app within a matter of seconds into a good looking

01:09:40.479 --> 01:09:44.720
app already. And then obviously you need to take care of like placement of stuff,

01:09:44.720 --> 01:09:51.040
how you're going to display your graphs, et cetera. But bs4dash already gives you like the

01:09:51.040 --> 01:09:55.919
basic layout for a great app, including like these little nice tools that you want to have,

01:09:55.919 --> 01:10:00.879
like a dark mode, light mode, interactive components, a sidebar that kind of,

01:10:02.799 --> 01:10:09.680
it goes away nicely, et cetera. Maximizing full screen, mobile friendly. So yeah, definitely.

01:10:10.560 --> 01:10:16.319
Indeed, that bs4dash we should put in. Well, thank you. I just put that one in the chat too.

