Okay. Let me just see. I'll go through just a few more questions here. But someone asked

01:10:24.560 --> 01:10:31.040
anonymously, have you found a practical upper limit for users of a Shiny app above which

01:10:31.040 --> 01:10:35.919
performance suffers? So is there like a certain number of users you've seen?

01:10:36.640 --> 01:10:45.680
I don't think I've seen it like practically. We have like, I think, 70 users, but they're

01:10:45.680 --> 01:10:55.040
never accessing the content at the same time. So I didn't experience those. But I actually can

01:10:55.040 --> 01:11:00.720
kind of calculate how much we can handle because we have one server, which is RStudio Connect.

01:11:01.040 --> 01:11:08.080
And because we only allow one connection per session, I kind of can calculate how many sessions

01:11:08.080 --> 01:11:13.680
we can actually have. I think the kind of amount of simultaneous sessions we can have is like 50 or

01:11:13.680 --> 01:11:21.200
something. And we have five running for each of our main apps. So five for the API from the cloud

01:11:21.200 --> 01:11:26.640
data from the analytics of 15. So we have still an abundance of sessions that still can be used

01:11:26.720 --> 01:11:32.080
and spun up without us running into problems. And if you do run into problems, it's not like

01:11:32.080 --> 01:11:38.080
something breaks or explodes. No, your user just gets a friendly come back later or overloaded

01:11:38.080 --> 01:11:43.439
message. So even that is not the end of the world. You want to prevent it, but yeah.

01:11:45.200 --> 01:11:49.759
But it really depends on what machinery you put behind it. The bigger your machines,

01:11:50.399 --> 01:11:57.279
the more servers, yeah, the more it can handle. Awesome. I've just shared one in the chat,

01:11:57.279 --> 01:12:04.560
which originally just came to mind. It's the California state COVID dashboard. I know it

01:12:04.560 --> 01:12:10.879
had thousands of users. It was open to millions of citizens. So there's a blog post on that one,

